3. Compiling and installing Websh (Unix)
----------------------------------------

Requirements:
- Tcl 8.6 or newer (threaded build)
- GNU make

  cd src/unix
  autoconf            # only needed after editing configure.ac
  ./configure --with-tcl=/path/to/tcl/lib
  make
  make test           # expected: 465 passed, 5 skipped, 0 failed
  make install

Build targets:
- websh3.7.5          standalone binary (dynamically linked to libwebsh)
- libwebsh3.7.5.so    TEA-compliant shared library (Tcl package "websh")
- mod_websh3.7.5.so   Apache module (built automatically when headers found)

Install layout (prefix = /usr/local/tcl86):
- bin/websh3.7.5, bin/websh -> websh3.7.5
- lib/websh3.7.5/libwebsh3.7.5.so, lib/websh3.7.5/pkgIndex.tcl
- lib/libwebsh3.7.5.so -> websh3.7.5/libwebsh3.7.5.so
- lib/libwebsh.so -> libwebsh3.7.5.so
- lib/httpd/modules/mod_websh3.7.5.so  (Apache only)
- lib/httpd/modules/mod_websh.so -> mod_websh3.7.5.so  (Apache only)

On Linux, make install automatically runs ldconfig and restarts Apache
(systemctl restart apache2 / httpd) if the service exists.

To build without the Apache module:

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib --disable-apache

To force the Apache module (fail if headers are missing):

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib --enable-apache

APR and APU include paths are detected automatically via apr-1-config
and apu-1-config. Override if needed:

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib \
      --with-aprinclude=/path/to/apr/include

On macOS with Homebrew, Apache and APR paths are found automatically
for both Intel (/usr/local) and Apple Silicon (/opt/homebrew) — no
extra flags required.

To change the install prefix:

  ./configure --with-tcl=/usr/local/tcl86/lib --prefix=/opt


4. mod_websh: Websh as Apache Module
------------------------------------

Websh applications can run in CGI mode or as mod_websh, the Apache 2.4
module. mod_websh is built automatically when Apache headers are found.

Note: mod_websh is not compatible with mod_http2. Disable mod_http2 in
the Apache configuration when using mod_websh.

mod_websh manages a pool of Tcl interpreters to handle concurrent
requests efficiently. Refer to doc/mod_websh/README for configuration
details.


